##Nurse: LET'S REFUEL TOGETHER! Because I'm homesick.

Micro signal

Function description, we are with you in this battle

Since January 22, polly has been in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital for support. Her previous work and old age, death, this came to the Golden Pool to help patients, may also be the fate of heaven.

By Wu Yunbo

The last time we spoke, polly told me that her father had died in a car accident two years ago, and her mother had died late last year. This year's New Year Plan, was prepared to pay tribute to them, but also want to do a good job for the living mother-in-law filial piety.

Many times, she said to me, "we are not so miserable, anyway, I think it is OK, perhaps I am born in Wuhan more optimistic. "

Here's what she said:

I wouldn't be able to live with myself if I didn't sign up

I am a native of Qingshan, Wuhan. I am forty years old and have been a nurse for seventeen years. I was an out-patient nurse in a general hospital, this time because of the epidemic came to Golden Pool Hospital intensive care unit reinforcement.

Early on the morning of the 22nd, hospital leaders sent a message to the group, recruiting volunteers to go to the major hospitals to support the epidemic. When my husband heard the news, he was dead set against it. He thinks I'm too old to risk my life for this, and it's not worth it. It's something young people do.

But I still signed up, I feel as a party member, do not sign up, do not need others to say, my own heart is hard.

When I first signed up, I thought that if I was chosen, I would probably be assigned to the big hospital near my home and maybe come back every once in a while.

On the morning of the 22nd, our leaders informed me that I was elected, the afternoon let me prepare to go, fast go when I know the original is the gold and silver lake. Before I left, my husband had a lot of anger towards me, and he didn't really talk to me. I did not care about him, after dinner, a simple package of clothes, picked up the bag turned out of the house.

It was cold outside, a cold wind was blowing, and I began to think back to the news I had heard recently. Although the epidemic had not been widely noticed at the time, friends and colleagues working in the hospitals were surrounded by infected health care workers. And with the recent increase in outpatient visits, I began to worry that I didn't have enough experience with infectious diseases to become infected.

Out of the neighborhood, get in the car, feel home away from me more and more.

Although the heart is very uneasy, but there is also a sense of duty, as if soldiers want to go to war. Before the outbreak of SARS, I just work for a long time, and at that time the situation in Wuhan is relatively light, the basic experience of the atmosphere of the extraordinary period. This time the responsibility finally fell to me.

The car is on the road, I do not have any redundant ideas, comfort myself probably only a week or two, we should be able to control this disease. After that, maybe you can go home before the Lantern Festival and get together with your family again.

Toward evening, I received a text from my husband apologizing. He said he had a bad attitude and should give me his full support in my work. The thought of going to a strange environment to work, but also to face unknown viruses, and a variety of challenges, I was a little bit out of control, tears.

We arrived at treasure pond on the 22nd at 8:00 p.m. As soon as I got out of the car, before I could clear my luggage, I was put on the night shift and started to work.

Golden Pool Hospital in the rain

The next morning, I heard the news of the siege, and I was alarmed. As soon as I checked in, there were a lot of new patients, and a dozen or so spare beds quickly filled up.

I saw a lot of ambulances outside the window, bringing patients in bed by bed. I also have a lot of other hospitals in the province to come to reinforce the medical staff.

I found that the situation was much more serious than I had expected, and I had a feeling that it would be hard to go home afterwards.

I miss my old life

This bad feeling was soon replaced by busyness at work. The first few days were the most intense, with new patients coming into the department to check in, and I had to get used to the pace of work. During that time, I worked about ten hours a day, counting the shifts.

The hospital schedule, the memos

In addition, because it was the beginning of the outbreak, a lot of supplies and logistics didn't catch up. The quality level of protective clothing is not up to scratch, the quality of that batch of bad, we need to use their own adhesive tape. In the event of a shortage of disposable isolation clothing, we have to wear the usual surgical clothes inside, each time after careful disinfection.

Because of the running-in of the shift, there are three layers of protection needed to change clothes, disinfection time, I missed several times to eat. The cold food was hard to swallow, and for several late nights I ate only the snacks and instant noodles I had been sent from the hospital.

In my intensive care unit, there are six nurses and two doctors working at the same time, responsible for about 30 patients. Patient beds are numbered according to the severity of the condition, with the most severe 4-5 patients being attended by 2 nurses.

If we can't control their condition, we'll move them to the ICU. In remission, we'll move them to another ICU.

Around the 26th, all the beds in my department were full, and my work became more and more regular. We usually work 8-9 hours a day, including disinfection and shift changes. Look at the weekly personal schedule, you can get a day or so of rest.

The daily wear of protective clothing makes my work particularly inconvenient. Some of the usual simple movements become very slow and difficult under protective clothing.

More inconvenient is to go to the toilet, so we do not dare to drink porridge and milk for breakfast, also do not dare to drink more water during the break, in case of an emergency, waste a suit of protective clothing not to say, but also delayed a very long working time.

Change Protective clothing

In fact, physical fatigue can also bear, the greater pressure from the psychological fear.

I take my temperature twice a day and have a CT scan every few days to make sure I'm not infected. Last time I had a C.T. , it showed some inflammation in my lungs, and the Chief of radiology called and told me to take a few more days off. The CT results were positive. It's not a viral infection. I'm still scared, but I'm working again.

I've been missing my life lately, being carefree and free, but now it's all so far away.

Death is common here, but we choose to be strong

One of the biggest differences from our regular jobs is that we front-line nurses also play the role of nurse. So it gives me a chance to spend more time with older patients.

There is an old man who is blind. He has no way to take care of himself. We need to feed him and take care of him.

Although he was blind, he came in his right mind and in his right mind. I'm in my 70s and I still have a lot of energy. I do everything I can. Every time we help him, he would say, "thank you, thank you, I'm really sorry to trouble you, " because he was loud, so I was very impressed with him.

But when I came back after two days of rest, his condition suddenly deteriorated. We hooked him up to a bunch of machines, and we moved him to the ICU pretty quickly.

I looked at him through the glass in the hallway and felt as if he had lost his energy. That was the last time I saw him, and according to colleagues in other departments, he passed away within a few days of his transfer.

Death is common here, but unlike in the past, there are no families, no farewell ceremonies, and tears and pain do not come with each passing life.

After doing some basic processing, we'll wrap the victim up, put him out in the hallway, or somewhere where the patient can't see him, and call the funeral home. I don't know how to describe it. It's just sad.

Every time I hear patients and their families on the phone in the ward, I feel sorry for them, and I think of my daughter, who is now in grade three, and the old man in my family.

For the first few days, my daughter cried every time she called me, as if I would never come back.

I can only tell her the story of the patients with mild illness in the ward, said that there are several uncles in the ward every day to do funny gymnastics, there is a grandfather in Tai Chi, Tai Chi played and pulled our medical staff to play a joke, thank us. It was the only way my daughter would be comfortable with me spending so much time on the sidelines that I couldn't go home.

I really hope that she can be calm about this matter, and learn to think rationally. Now, she doesn't worry so much. She just hangs up the phone and says, "mom, you have to be okay! "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The whole process, I would like to thank my family several old people, they assume a lot of my family responsibilities. I can't go to work every day until they're safe.

I've also been watching videos on facebook of doctors crying and nurses freaking out.

But that's not the case in our department. It could be that Wuhan people are naturally optimistic, or it could be that colleagues from various hospitals have already done some psychological construction before. Usually encountered those more difficult moments, the nurses in our department will support each other, gradually also formed a spiritual strength.

As medical workers, we need to be strong, society also needs us to be strong.

There are no ifs in this world

But we all know what we're doing

In order to prevent the outside bacteria and viruses, the medical staff's mobile phones are not allowed to bring into the isolation ward. So for the macro-control of the epidemic and data updates, we have not even outside the timely understanding of the people.

There's been a tremendous amount of panic about the numbers, but as a paramedic, I can't panic. I would like to believe that the gradual increase in the number represents the continuation of systematic relief efforts, with more people receiving medical help. I want to reassure my patients with my expertise.

At the same time, shortages are a real problem for our first line of care. But when I saw that all the hospital administrators are busy with this, I feel I should not have too many complaints. They've worked hard enough. The most important thing for everyone in the hospital is that the patients are treated and well fed.

And I am glad that there are many volunteers, for us to send the need for fruit and supplies, there is a sense of unity, let me feel very practical.

POLLY's tag

Recently, there are many reports about Dr. Li Wenliang on the Internet. As a medical staff, I feel very sorry for Dr. Li. I can understand that people are not in a good mood right now, and will make some emotional points.

But as a medical professional, I think in the early days of infectious diseases, personal knowledge of the virus is really very limited. It's hard to predict the future of the virus, especially as it's highly contagious and can be transmitted through the respiratory tract.

There are no ifs in this world, but what I've learned so far, both collectively and individually, is that we're doing everything we can to fight this epidemic, and that's the most important thing right now.

In the last two days, the outbreak has been effectively controlled, many suspected personnel have been effectively quarantined, our department also has many patients into mild illness. As front-line personnel, we all know, and will do their part, hope that the situation will gradually become better.

POSTSCRIPT:

Since January 22, polly has been working in the intensive care unit of Golden Pond Hospital. She told me she wanted the epidemic to be over and people to be free again.

Before the story was finished, a recent video posted by Hubei Daily was shared on polly's facebook page. "Let's cheer together! Because I'm homesick, " she wrote below
